			<title>diGGin' Round: Further Adventures in Gate Opening</title>
            <link><![CDATA[http://traffic.libsyn.com/paullev/LOLT16-Digg.mp3]]></link>
            <description><![CDATA[<p>Welcome to Episode 16 of <font color="#cc6600">Li</font><font color="#ff3333">ght On Lig</font><font color="#cc6600">ht Thr</font><font color="#ff3300">ough</font><font color="#000000">: <em>diGGin' Round: Further Adventures in Gate-Opening</em>, in which I take a look at Digg, the fabulously popular online news system, in which readers not editors choose what is on the front page.&nbsp; Like Wikipedia, Digg (for the most part) is run by its users.&nbsp; Like Wiki, Digg suffers from vandals on the one hand and zealots who bury stories too quickly on the other.&nbsp; But at least Digg and Wikipedia are honest and open about how their articles are chosen - unlike the <em>New York Times</em>, for example, which says it publishes &quot;all the news that's fit to print,&quot; when in fact it's publishing all the news that a small group of editors deem fit to print.&nbsp; The Beatles were turned down by 26 record companies before someone had the sense to sign them.&nbsp; So much for experts and editors.&nbsp; Good for Digg for trying something different... (See also <a href="http://paullevinson.blogspot.com/2007/01/digg-and-wikipedia-further-adventures.html">Digg and Wikipedia: Further Adventures in Gate-Opening</a>.)</font></p>

<p>In addition to looking around Digg, I also had the pleasure of making guest appearances on a few podcasts this week, including Jake's <a href="http://notrightpodcast.com/">Just Not Right</a>&nbsp;and George's <a href="http://oneminutehowto.com/">One Minute How-To</a>&nbsp;- check 'em out ... And if you like brief pieces of advice on podcasts, give a listen to my latest podcast, <a href="http://www.10minutelessons.com/index.html?Expert=17&Reload=1">Ask Lev</a>&nbsp;over on 10minutelessons.com...</p>

<p>Enjoy...</p>

<p>Paul</p>

